TY  - JOUR
T1  - Optimal Unemployment Insurance
AU  - Hopenhayn, Hugo A.
AU  - Nicolini, Juan Pablo
Y1  - 1997/04/01
PY  - 1997
DA  - 1997/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/262078
DO  - 10.1086/262078
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 412
EP  - 438
VL  - 105
IS  - 2
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper considers the design of an optimal unemployment insurance system. The problem is modeled as a repeated principalagent problem involving a risk?averse agent?the unemployed worker?and a risk?neutral principal, which cannot monitor the agent's search effort. The optimal long?term contract subject to the associated incentive constraints is characterized. This contract involves a replacement ratio that decreases throughout the unemployment spell and a wage tax after reemployment that, under some mild regularity conditions, increases with the lenght of the unemployment spell. Some numerical results are presented that suggest that the gains from switching to this optimal unemployment insurance scheme could be quite large. The performance of this optimal contract is also compared to alternative liquidity provision mechanisms.
AB  - This paper considers the design of an optimal unemployment insurance system. The problem is modeled as a repeated principalagent problem involving a risk?averse agent?the unemployed worker?and a risk?neutral principal, which cannot monitor the agent's search effort. The optimal long?term contract subject to the associated incentive constraints is characterized. This contract involves a replacement ratio that decreases throughout the unemployment spell and a wage tax after reemployment that, under some mild regularity conditions, increases with the lenght of the unemployment spell. Some numerical results are presented that suggest that the gains from switching to this optimal unemployment insurance scheme could be quite large. The performance of this optimal contract is also compared to alternative liquidity provision mechanisms.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/262078
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/262078
Y2  - 2024/03/23
